    <h3>Age-Related Macular Degeneration Overview</h3>
    <div class="snippet_fmt" id="art-snp">
     <h3>What Is Age-Related Macular Degeneration?</h3>
     <p>Macular degeneration is the leading cause of severe vision loss in people over age 60. It occurs when the small central portion of the retina, known as the macula, deteriorates. The retina is the light-sensing nerve tissue at the back of the eye. Because the disease develops as a person ages, it is often referred to as age-related macular degeneration (AMD). Although macular degeneration is almost never a totally blinding condition, it can be a source of significant visual disability.</p>
     <p>There are two main types of age-related macular degeneration:</p>
